  "prompt": "What is the legal status of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. It is the process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity, such as drug trafficking or terrorist funding, appear to have come from a legitimate source. The money from the criminal activity is considered \"dirty,\" and the process \"launders\" it to make it look \"clean.\"\n\nThe legal status of money laundering is such that it is a criminal offense, and it is punishable by law. The specific laws and penalties vary by country, but generally, they include significant fines and imprisonment. Financial institutions are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to prevent and detect money laundering activities.\n\nFor example, in the United States, money laundering is an offense under the Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 and subsequent laws, including the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986. Similar legislation exists in other countries, such as the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 in the United Kingdom.\n\nInternational efforts to combat money laundering include the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have adopted the FATF recommendations into their national laws.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious crime with significant legal repercussions. It undermines the integrity of financial institutions and systems, and it is a global priority to combat this illegal activity.",
